Creating accounts on LinkedIn, Kaggle, and GitHub felt like a small but important step toward building my professional identity as a college student. Each platform pushes me to think more seriously about how I present my skills, interests, and work to the outside world.

On LinkedIn, I became more aware of my academic journey, projects, and goals, because I had to write them clearly in my profile instead of keeping them only in my head. It made me realize that networking isn’t just for “later” but something I can start now by connecting with classmates, seniors, and professionals in my field. This also motivated me to be more intentional about the kind of image and footprint I create online.

Creating a Kaggle account reminded me that learning data science and machine learning is not just about theory but also about practice and community. Seeing real datasets, notebooks, and competitions made me understand where my current skills stand and how much more I can improve. It encouraged me to be okay with being a beginner, to learn from others’ work, and to slowly start contributing my own notebooks and solutions.

GitHub, on the other hand, made my coding work feel more “real” and long-term. By putting my projects and experiments there, I started thinking about writing cleaner code, better documentation, and using version control properly instead of just saving random files on my laptop. It also gave me a place to gradually build a portfolio that I can show to future recruiters, collaborators, or mentors.
